        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Cincinnati Sept 22 1881.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S. Morais.<lb/>
                Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear friend&#8212;your truly<lb/> welcome favour reached me&#44; with<lb/> kind expressions of sympathy you<lb/> manifest toward self and family<lb/> on account of the calamity which<lb/> <sic>befel</sic> us a few days since&#44; we<lb/> thank God that all are safe and<lb/> well&#44; ample time to dress and<lb/> get out the building ere the crash<lb/> came.  The large factory adjoining<lb/> us that took to fire was eight <del>stores</del><lb/> stories in height and our house<lb/> on three&#44; so you may well imag&#45;<lb/>ine that when the crash came<lb/> by the falling of the walls on our<lb/> house it was pretty severe&#44; it oc&#45;<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>at half past one Thursday morning<lb/> Esther&#44; Henry&#44; Sallie and self had<lb/> only been in bed about half an<lb/> hour when the fire cry was raised.<lb/>  So we got up and the blaze was<lb/> pouring out the 7<hi rend="sup">th</hi> story windows<lb/> of the factory&#44; so we dressed and<lb/> got out some few moments ere the<lb/> walls fell.  We left every thing &#38;<lb/> went out as we were fully in&#45;<lb/>sured&#44; and will come out right.<lb/>  Still I lose many things that has<lb/> no intrinsic value to any one<lb/> but to myself.  We thank God for<lb/> his kind Providence extended to&#45;<lb/>ward us.<lb/></p>
            <p>We were in hopes dear Nina<lb/> would have escaped the Hayfever<lb/> I suppose she is now home with<lb/> you&#44; extend love from all to her.<lb/></p> 
            <p>You must excuse brevity of this<lb/> will write more anon.<lb/></p>
            <p>May God bless you all with<lb/> with a New Year of health and hap&#45;<lb/>piness.  As ever truly &#38;<lb/>
                Jacob Ezekiel<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
